      "text": "Hi Marc,\n\nI promised to email you while we were chatting at the ISSS meeting yesterday.  You wanted to swap views on the relevance of \"images of the future\", if I recall the conversation correctly.\n\n\nBasically, my view is that, in the Maslovian manner, we prioritise our needs and engage in satisfying them in a rough priority order, i.e. physiological, social, then growth. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "711ad5e52961d9ef",
      "text": "Immediacy, as opposed to long-termism also has a significant part to play in our priorities. This has an evolutionary basis and best satisfies our core need to survive and propagate our genome. \nThere are several things about \"images of the future\" driving social change that bother me. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "7955b9ef0a2ba7c6",
      "text": "I'm not convinced that a society has a common image. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "2e3ce97ba3255b44",
      "text": "\"Images of the future\" are to some extent cultural, but also largely personal.  Often there are several and, frequently, they are in conflict. Also, as someone mentioned at the meeting (apologies if it was you), such images are about our need for meaning. Meaning is quite a high level growth need, a long-term concern, and only really something we can attempt to satisfy once our more basic needs are adequately attended to. You, I, and many of the people at the meeting are probably in the fortunate position of being able to do this. However, I would argue that most of the population isn't. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "1822992623340289",
      "text": "The struggle to make a living is so intense that even very intelligent people have little time to pursue that form of growth.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "29e24d1abcf7b75d",
      "text": "There are a couple of ways in which it might be possible. Some adopt ready made images from religion or politics, and that has to do. However, the number of options to chose from is vast. So again, there is not a common image. Images may also cascade down from leaders to followers, but again **we can chose** to follow one of several leaders, and so there are multiple images. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ac53bd31b41c0cdc",
      "text": "I think that the best we can say about images is that the way in which they interact in a society has some influence on the nature of its progress. Providing, of course, that we live in stable times.\n\nFinally, for there to be a single image driving society forward there would have to be a consensus on what it is. We do not have that. Rather we have over seven billion single consciousness which interact, sometimes positively and oft times negatively. This in my view is one of the reasons we are unable to tackle threats such as climate change.\n\nHappy to be proven wrong about this, of course.\n\nwith best wishes,\n\nJohn"
